# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1935-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The **1935 Detroit Tigers** won the 1935 World Series, defeating the Chicago Cubs 4 games to 2.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The season was their 35th since they entered the American League in 1901.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] It was the first World Series championship for the Tigers.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] As the 1934 Detroit Tigers won a club-record 101 games, the team made few changes in the off-season to alter their winning combination.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Hall of Famer Mickey Cochrane returned as the team's manager and catcher.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Known as "Black Mike", Cochrane is considered one of the greatest catchers of all time.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In 1935, he hit .319 (9th in the AL) with a .452 on-base percentage (3rd in the AL), 96 walks (4th in the AL), 93 runs scored, and 33 doubles.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Aside from his contributions as a player, Cochrane was invaluable as a manager and leader.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Charlie Gehringer later said: "When Mickey was managing the Tigers from behind the plate I can't remember him ever fouling up anything.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Detroit infield of the 1934–1935 seasons was one of the best-hitting combinations in MLB history.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Shortstop **Billy Rogell** hit .275 and scored 88 runs in 1935 while drawing 80 walks.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Rogell also led AL shortstops with 104 double plays and a .971 fielding percentage.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Rogell and Gehringer played over 1,000 games together as the Tigers' double play combination.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Rogell's fiery demeanor was a stark contrast to the calm, quiet demeanor of Gehringer.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Once, after both failed to cover second on a steal attempt, Mickey Cochrane charged out from behind the plate shouting at Rogell and Gehringer.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] As reported in *The New Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract*: "Rogell, astonished, looked at Gehringer to see if he was going to say anything.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Gehringer, of course, had nothing to say.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] 'Don't you come charging out here telling me how to play shortstop.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] You go back there and do the catching, and I'll play shortstop.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Rounding out the infield was utility infielder **Flea Clifton**.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Clifton played in 43 games during the 1935 regular season, with a .255 batting average.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] However, when Hank Greenberg broke his wrist in Game 2 of the 1935 World Series, Marv Owen moved to first base, and Clifton stepped in as the starting third baseman.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Clifton was 0-for-16 with 4 strikeouts in the Series.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Clifton had been teammates with Hank Greenberg in the minor leagues, and the two became friends.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In his autobiography, Greenberg joked about Clifton's unusual diet: "On the road, he used to eat nothing but doughnuts and bananas.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] He said they were cheap and filling and stretched his meal money.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In the outfield, Hall of Famer Goose Goslin played in left field.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The speedy Jo-Jo White and Gee Walker shared responsibility for center field, with White playing in 98 games.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Center fielder **Jo-Jo White** led the team with 19 stolen bases and also contributed 12 triples.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] White's real first name was Joyner, but he was called "Jo-Jo" because of the way he pronounced his native state of Georgia.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers fourth outfielder, **Gee Walker** played 45 games in center field but also covered 29 games in left and 11 games in right.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Known as "The Madman from Mississippi", Walker was a fiery competitor and a clown.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] He hit over .300 for the 1935 Tigers, but his reputation for being inattentive and overzealous on the basepaths drew the ire of manager Mickey Cochrane.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1934 World Series, he was picked off first while arguing with the Cardinals' bench.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] On another occasion, he tried to steal a base while the batter was being given an intentional walk.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The pitching staff was led by starters Tommy Bridges, Schoolboy Rowe, Alvin Crowder, and Elden Auker.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] After making a big splash in 1934 with an American League record 16 consecutive wins, **Schoolboy Rowe** had another big year in 1935.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Schoolboy had become a fan favorite not only for his pitching performance in 1934 but for his nationally publicized romance.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] While appearing on the Eddie Cantor radio show, Rowe famously asked his fiancée, "How'm I doing, Edna honey?" The line endeared Schoolboy to the nation, and also resulted in relentless teasing from opposing players and fans.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Schoolboy and Edna married after the 1934 season and had their first child during the 1935 season.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Schoolboy led the league in 1935 with six shutouts and finished the season with a 19–13 record in 34 starts.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Despite a 2.51 ERA in the 1935 World Series, Rowe had a 1–2 record.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] He was the losing pitcher in Game 1, despite striking out 8 batters, pitching a complete game and allowing only 2 earned runs.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 3, Rowe got the win, pitching 4 innings in relief.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] But Game 5 was another tough loss, as Schoolboy threw a complete game and allowed 2 earned runs, but the Tigers scored only once.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers' #4 starter was 36-year-old **Alvin Crowder**, who served in the U.S.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Army during its occupation of Siberia after World War I.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Crowder, known as "General", was 16–10 in his 32 starts.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The General pitched a complete game in Game 4 of the 1935 World Series for a 2–1 victory.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Crowder pitched in three World Series consecutively (1933–1935), posting a record of 1–2 with 3.81 ERA in 26 innings pitched.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers' main reliever in 1935 was **Elon Hogsett**, who appeared in 40 games, finishing 30, with an ERA of 3.54.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit — the defending American League champion — finished 93–58, three games ahead of the second place New York Yankees.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The 1935 Tigers outscored their opponents 919 to 665.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] After losing the 1934 World Series in a close seven-game series with the Gashouse Gang from St.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Louis, the Tigers were determined to win the first championship for the City of Detroit since the Detroit Wolverines won the National League pennant in 1887.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Schoolboy Rowe lost on Opening Day, and the Tigers were 2–9 after two weeks of play.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] At the end of April, the Tigers were in last place.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] By the end of May, the Tigers had started to turn things around but still had a mediocre 20–18 record.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] On June 25, 1935, the Yankees were in first place, and the Tigers were still playing unexceptionally with a record of 33–28.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] However, the Tigers got red hot after that, going 35–10 between June 26 and August 15, 1935.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] During that period, they put together win streaks of 10 games (June 30 to July 7) and 9 games (July 31 to August 11).
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] It was during the second streak on July 26 when the Tigers passed the Yankees and moved into first place for good.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit remained hot through Labor Day, with a record of 85–44 and 10-game lead over the Yankees on the morning of September 8.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] But the Tigers' bats went cold during the last three weeks of the season as the team went 8–14 to close the regular season.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Despite losing 14 of their final 22 games, the Tigers clinched their second straight American League pennant on September 21 by winning both games of a double-header against the St.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Tommy Bridges won the opener, 6–2, and Elden Auker pitched a complete-game shutout to win the second game, 2–0.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The **1935 World Series** featured the Detroit Tigers and the Chicago Cubs, with the Tigers winning in six games for their first championship in five World Series appearances.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Cubs had the better regular season record and had a 21-game win streak during the pennant stretch.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers, on the other hand, went 8–14 in their last 22 games.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Based on momentum, it appeared the Cubs would roll past the Tigers.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Cubs won Game 1, 3–0, on a 4-hit shutout by pitcher Lon Warneke.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers evened the Series in Game 2, with an 8–3 win, but the Tigers lost Hank Greenberg who fractured his left wrist when colliding with Cubs catcher Gabby Hartnett.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Greenberg had tried to score from first on a single.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] He finished the game, but he developed severe pain on the train ride to Chicago that night, and x-rays revealed fractures of two bones in his wrist.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Greenberg was sidelined for the rest of the Series, and Mickey Cochrane was left to decide who could replace Greenberg.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Initially, Cochrane decided to play first base himself and have backup catcher Ray Hayworth take over at catcher.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] But Tigers owner Frank Navin ordered Cochrane to move third baseman Marv Owen to first base and play utility infielder Flea Clifton at third base.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Cochrane disagreed, as Clifton was the weakest hitter on the team, and Owen was in a slump.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Navin insisted, and Owen went one for twenty in the Series, while Flea went 0-for-16 in the Series.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 3, the Cubs tied the game in the bottom of the 9th, but the Tigers won it with an unearned run in the 11th inning.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In the 3rd inning, umpire George Moriarty (who had played for the Tigers from 1909 to 1915 and managed the Tigers from 1927 to 1928) called Phil Cavarretta out in a close play at second base.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] When the Cubs protested, Moriarty verbally abused the Cubs, and ejected Cubs' manager Charlie Grimm and player Bill Jurges.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] After the game, Grimm said: "If a manager can't go out and make a decent kick, what the hell is the game coming to?
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] I didn't swear at him but he swore at us." Coach Roy Johnson accused Moriarty of making improper reflections on the Cubs' ancestry.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Judge Landis later levied $200 fines on Moriarty‚ Grimm‚ and Jurges for their conduct in the World Series.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 4, Alvin Crowder pitched a 2–1 complete game victory.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers won on an unearned run in the 6th inning.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 5, Cubs' pitcher Lon Warneke kept the Cubs alive with 6 innings of shutout ball for his 2nd win.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Cubs won 3–1 on a 2-run home run by Chuck Klein off losing pitcher Schoolboy Rowe.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In Game 6, Tommy Bridges pitched a complete game victory to win the Series for Detroit.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] With the score tied 3–3 in the top of the 9th inning, Bridges gave up a leadoff triple to Stan Hack, but retired the next three batters without the runner on third scoring.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] In the bottom of the 9th, Goose Goslin drove in the winning run with 2 outs.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] After the game, manager Mickey Cochrane said the following of Bridges' gutsy performance: "A hundred and fifty pounds of courage.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Delirious Detroit fans rushed onto Navin Field in celebration after Goslin's game-winning hit.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The celebration spilled out onto Michigan Avenue and Trumbull.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] People from throughout Detroit flooded the central city in a celebration that newspapers reported went on until three in the morning.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] For a few hours, the worries of the Great Depression were gone and the only thing that mattered was the Tigers.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit owner Frank Navin, then 64 years old, had been running the organization for 30 years and had seen four of his teams win American League pennants, only to lose four World Series.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] On November 13, 1935, five weeks after the Tigers finally won the World Series, Navin suffered a heart attack while riding a horse and died.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] When the Tigers won the 1935 World Series, the City of Detroit was mired in the Great Depression, which had hit Detroit and its industries particularly hard.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] The Detroit Lions also won the 1935 NFL Championship Game, and the Detroit Red Wings won the 1935–36 Stanley Cup championship, but the biggest celebration came when the Tigers won the World Series, as the "City of Champions" moniker took hold.
[src:1935-detroit-tigers-season/1935-detroit-tigers-season] Baseball was hugely popular in Detroit during the Great Depression, as attendance at Navin Field in 1934 and 1935, accounted for nearly 25 percent of baseball's total paid attendance.
